  "prompt": "Which is more acidic phenol or paranitro phenol?",
  "response": "Paranitrophenol is more acidic than phenol. \n\nThe increased acidity of paranitrophenol can be attributed to the presence of the nitro group (-NO2) at the para position relative to the hydroxyl group (-OH). The nitro group is an electron-withdrawing group due to its strong -I (inductive) and -M (mesomeric) effects. This electron-withdrawing nature stabilizes the negative charge on the phenoxide ion (the conjugate base formed when phenol donates a proton) more effectively than in phenol itself. Therefore, paranitrophenol has a lower pKa and is more acidic compared to phenol.",
